INSERT INTO `overviews` (`id`, `P_id`, `question`, `answare`, `slug`, `sequece`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(3, '3', 'What is Sergel 40 mg Capsule??', 'Sergel 40 mg Capsule is a proton pump inhibitor (PPI). PPIs work by reducing the amount of acid produced in the stomach. Sergel 40 mg Capsule is used to treat gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD), ulcers, and other conditions that involve too much stomach acid.', 'what-is-sergel-40-mg-capsule', NULL, '2024-09-12 00:18:58', '2024-09-12 00:18:58'),
(4, '3', 'What is Sergel 40 mg Capsule used for?', 'Sergel 40 mg Capsule has multiple uses. It eases heartburn and relieves GERD symptoms. It also aids in healing erosive esophagitis, a condition caused by stomach acid damaging the esophagus lining. Additionally, Sergel 40 mg Capsule effectively prevents erosive esophagitis recurrence.', 'what-is-sergel-40-mg-capsule-used-for', NULL, '2024-09-12 00:19:54', '2024-09-12 00:19:54'),
(5, '3', 'What are the side effects of Sergel 40 mg Capsule?', 'Sergel 40 mg Capsule may cause common side effects like headaches, diarrhea, nausea, gas, stomach pain, constipation, and dry mouth. There aren\'t any differences in the types of side effects between long-term (up to 12 months) and short-term use.', 'what-are-the-side-effects-of-sergel-40-mg-capsule', NULL, '2024-09-12 00:20:09', '2024-09-12 00:20:09'),
(6, '3', 'Can I take Sergel 40 mg Capsule if I am pregnant or breastfeeding?', 'Sergel 40 mg Capsule doesn\'t have any side-effects if you are pregnant or breastfeeding. You still should talk to your doctor about the risks and benefits of taking Sergel 40 mg Capsule.', 'can-i-take-sergel-40-mg-capsule-if-i-am-pregnant-or-breastfeeding', NULL, '2024-09-12 00:20:31', '2024-09-12 00:20:31'),
(7, '3', 'How long does it take for Sergel 40 mg Capsule to work?', 'Sergel 40 mg Capsule usually starts to work within a few hours of taking it.', 'how-long-does-it-take-for-sergel-40-mg-capsule-to-work', NULL, '2024-09-12 00:20:46', '2024-09-12 00:20:46'),
(8, '3', 'Quick Tips?', 'It is a well-tolerated medicine and provides relief for a long time.\r\n\r\nAvoid eating late at night or before bedtime.\r\n\r\nInform your doctor if you get watery diarrhea, fever or stomach pain that does not go away.\r\n\r\nLong-term use of Sergel 20 can cause weak bones and a deficiency of minerals such as magnesium. Take adequate dietary intake of calcium and magnesium or their supplements as prescribed by your doctor.\r\n\r\nConsult your doctor right away if you develop decreased urination, edema (swelling due to fluid retention), lower back pain, nausea, fatigue, and rash or fever. These could be signs of a kidney problem.', 'quick-tips', NULL, '2024-09-12 00:21:06', '2024-09-12 00:21:06'),
(9, '4', 'What is Alcet, and what is it used for?', 'Alcet is an oral solution containing Levocetirizine Dihydrochloride. It is used to treat symptoms associated with allergic conditions such as perennial allergic rhinitis, seasonal allergic rhinitis, and chronic idiopathic urticaria.', 'what-is-alcet-and-what-is-it-used-for', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:28:50', '2024-09-12 01:28:50'),
(10, '4', 'How does Alcet work?', 'Alcet contains Levocetirizine, the active isomer of cetirizine. It is a highly effective and well-tolerated nonsedating antihistamine with potent antiallergic properties. It acts rapidly and has a long-lasting effect, allowing for once-a-day administration.', 'how-does-alcet-work', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:30:38', '2024-09-12 01:30:38'),
(11, '4', 'What is the recommended dosage for Alcet?', 'For adults and children 12 years and older, the recommended dose is 5 mg once daily. Children aged 6 to 11 should take 2.5 mg (equivalent to ½ tablet or 1 teaspoon oral solution) once daily. Children aged 6 months to 5 years should take 1.25 mg (½ teaspoon oral solution) once daily.', 'what-is-the-recommended-dosage-for-alcet', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:31:26', '2024-09-12 01:31:26'),
(12, '4', 'Are there any special instructions for certain groups?', 'The dosage may vary for specific groups, such as those with renal impairment. In mild impairment, a dose of 2.5 mg once daily is recommended, whereas in severe impairment, a dose of 2.5 mg twice weekly is advised. Always consult a healthcare professional for personalized advice.', 'are-there-any-special-instructions-for-certain-groups', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:31:41', '2024-09-12 01:31:41'),
(13, '4', 'What are the contraindications of Alcet?', 'Alcet should not be used by individuals with hypersensitivity to levocetirizine, cetirizine, or its parent compound hydroxyzine. It is contraindicated in patients with severe renal impairment.', 'what-are-the-contraindications-of-alcet', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:31:56', '2024-09-12 01:31:56'),
(14, '4', 'Are there any side effects of Alcet?', 'Generally, Alcet is well-tolerated. Rare side effects may include headache, dry mouth, fatigue, and skin rash.', 'are-there-any-side-effects-of-alcet', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:32:26', '2024-09-12 01:32:26'),
(15, '4', 'Can Alcet be used during pregnancy and lactation?', 'Alcet falls under Pregnancy Category B. While there are no adequate and well-controlled studies in pregnant women, it should be used during pregnancy only if clearly needed. It is excreted in breast milk, so caution is advised during lactation.', 'can-alcet-be-used-during-pregnancy-and-lactation', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:32:38', '2024-09-12 01:32:38'),
(16, '4', 'What precautions and warnings should be considered?', 'Alcet should be used with caution in epileptic patients, those at risk of convulsions, individuals with renal impairment, and during pregnancy and lactation.', 'what-precautions-and-warnings-should-be-considered', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:32:51', '2024-09-12 01:32:51'),
(17, '4', 'What should be done in case of overdose?', 'No clinically relevant adverse events have been reported in case of overdose. However, in the event of overdosage, symptomatic and supportive treatment is recommended.', 'what-should-be-done-in-case-of-overdose', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:33:07', '2024-09-12 01:33:07'),
(18, '4', 'What is the therapeutic class of Alcet?', 'Alcet belongs to the therapeutic class of non-sedating antihistamines.', 'what-is-the-therapeutic-class-of-alcet', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:33:16', '2024-09-12 01:33:16'),
(19, '4', 'How should Alcet be stored?', 'Alcet should be stored at a temperature not exceeding 30°C in a dry place and protected from light.', 'how-should-alcet-be-stored', NULL, '2024-09-12 01:33:27', '2024-09-12 01:33:27'),
(20, '14', 'What drug interactions should I be aware of when using Cleocin (Clindamycin)?', 'Cleocin enhances the effect of neuromuscular blocking agents and should be used cautiously with patients receiving these drugs. There is antagonism between Cleocin and erythromycin, so these two drugs should not be used together.', 'what-drug-interactions-should-i-be-aware-of-when-using-cleocin-clindamycin', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:19:40', '2024-10-08 12:19:40'),
(21, '14', 'Who should not take Clindamycin (Cleocin)?', 'Clindamycin is contraindicated for patients who are sensitive to clindamycin or any other ingredients in this medication.', 'who-should-not-take-clindamycin-cleocin', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:20:07', '2024-10-08 12:20:07'),
(22, '14', 'What are the possible side effects of Cleocin?', 'The common side effects include abdominal pain, esophagitis, esophageal ulcer, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, itching (pruritus), skin rashes, and hives (urticaria).', 'what-are-the-possible-side-effects-of-cleocin', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:20:29', '2024-10-08 12:20:29'),
(23, '14', 'Can pregnant or breastfeeding women use Cleocin?', 'Cleocin falls under Pregnancy Category B. It crosses the placenta, and its concentration in amniotic fluid is approximately 30% of the maternal concentration. It should only be used during pregnancy if absolutely necessary. Clindamycin may also appear in breast milk, so it is not recommended for nursing mothers unless clearly needed.', 'can-pregnant-or-breastfeeding-women-use-cleocin', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:20:50', '2024-10-08 12:20:50'),
(24, '14', 'What precautions should be taken when using Cleocin?', 'Cleocin should be used with caution in patients with a history of gastrointestinal disease, particularly colitis.', 'what-precautions-should-be-taken-when-using-cleocin', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:21:11', '2024-10-08 12:21:11'),
(25, '14', 'Is Clindamycin safe for newborns and elderly patients?', 'For newborns and infants (up to 16 years old), organ functions should be carefully monitored while taking Cleocin. For elderly patients, no dosage adjustment is typically necessary.', 'is-clindamycin-safe-for-newborns-and-elderly-patients', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:21:35', '2024-10-08 12:21:35'),
(26, '14', 'What should I do in case of an overdose of Cleocin?', 'Overdosage of Cleocin is rare, but similar adverse reactions to those seen with regular doses may occur. Unexpected reactions could happen, and in such cases, simple gastric lavage may be performed. Haemodialysis and peritoneal dialysis are not effective in removing Cleocin from the body. No specific antidote is known.', 'what-should-i-do-in-case-of-an-overdose-of-cleocin', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:21:56', '2024-10-08 12:21:56'),
(27, '14', 'How should Cleocin powder for oral solution be prepared?', 'To reconstitute Cleocin powder for oral solution, first, shake the bottle to loosen the powder. Add 80 ml of boiled and cooled water to the dry mixture, in two portions, shaking well after each addition. The reconstituted solution should be used within 2 weeks if kept at room temperature', 'how-should-cleocin-powder-for-oral-solution-be-prepared', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:22:18', '2024-10-08 12:22:18'),
(28, '14', 'How should Cleocin be diluted for intravenous administration?', 'For IV administration, Cleocin phosphate must be diluted so that the concentration does not exceed 18 mg/ml. Infusion rates should not exceed 30 mg per minute, and more than 1200 mg in a single 1-hour infusion is not recommended. Intramuscular injections should not exceed 600 mg, and dilution is not required for IM administration.', 'how-should-cleocin-be-diluted-for-intravenous-administration', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:22:53', '2024-10-08 12:22:53'),
(29, '14', 'What is the stability of diluted Cleocin injection solutions?', 'Diluted Cleocin injection solutions remain stable for 16 days at 25°C (room temperature) and for 32 days at 4°C (refrigeration).', 'what-is-the-stability-of-diluted-cleocin-injection-solutions', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:23:08', '2024-10-08 12:23:08'),
(30, '14', 'What storage conditions are required for Cleocin?', 'Store Cleocin below 30°C, away from light and moisture. Keep the medication out of the reach of children.', 'what-storage-conditions-are-required-for-cleocin', NULL, '2024-10-08 12:23:29', '2024-10-08 12:23:29'),
